","role":"Commanded the 24th North Carolina Infantry, C.S.A.","battles":["Drewry's Bluff 1864"],"notes":"Wounded at Drewry's Bluff, 15 May 1864; captured near Dinwiddie Court House and imprisoned at Fort Delaware until July 1865."}],"career":[{"role":"Dean, School of Medicine","organization":"Washington University","location":"St. Louis, Missouri","start_year":1917,"end_year":1923},{"role":"Dean, Medical School","organization":"University of California","location":"Berkeley, California","start_year":1936}],"birth":{"year":1819,"month":8,"day":2,"city":"Raleigh","county":"Wake","state":"North Carolina","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1886,"month":1,"day":23,"city":"New Bern","county":"Craven","state":"North Carolina","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_name":"Cedar Grove Cemetery","city":"New Bern","county":"Craven","state":"North Carolina","country":"United States"},"slug":"william-john-clarke-1819"},"HD5937":{"id":"HD5937","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_thomas":9},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["education"],"notable_blurb":"Superintendent of the Michigan School for the Deaf","primary_url":"https://www.ncpedia.org/biography/clarke-francis-devereux"},"parents":{"father_id":"I01588","mother_id":"HD5936"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I01589","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":1}],"tags":["educator","freemason","civil_war","navy"],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"He fought at sea for the Confederacy","body":"Clarke served in the Confederate Navy aboard six vessels, rising to lieutenant and seeing action at Mobile Bay and City Point, where he was wounded. He left the sea to spend his life teaching the deaf."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"He led Michigan's deaf school for decades","body":"After years at the New York Institution for the Deaf, Clarke directed the Arkansas school and then, from 1892, the Michigan School for the Deaf at Flint. He published his Methods Used in the Michigan School for the Deaf in 1908."},{"number":3,"category":"education","header":"Engineering degrees came between his teaching posts","body":"Between stints at the New York deaf institution Clarke took a master's degree and a civil-engineering degree from Columbia and briefly practiced as an engineer. He kept returning to deaf education, the calling he found through a boyhood tutor."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"He died a grand master of Masons","body":"Clarke joined the Masons after moving to Michigan and was serving as grand master of the state's Grand Lodge when he died in 1913. His funeral was among the largest the city of Flint had ever seen."}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD0411","display_label":"founded the American School for the Deaf in 1817"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Francis Devereux","last_name":"Clarke","display_name":"Lt. Francis Devereux Clarke","gender":"male","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780855375/157925628_609ab74f-6906-460c-b985-61c353fa9497_a988xw.jpg"},"military_service":[],"career":[],"birth":{"year":1849,"month":1,"day":31,"city":"Raleigh","county":"Wake","state":"North Carolina","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1913,"month":9,"day":7,"city":"Flint","county":"Genesee","state":"Michigan","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_name":"Glenwood Cemetery","city":"Flint","county":"Genesee","state":"Michigan","country":"United States"},"education":[{"school_name":"Columbia University","type":"graduate","dates":"